/static/80eaf6e2e1268a1171bf679425c34a66/471ef/moniviestin-workflow.png 1185w&quot;
        sizes=&quot;(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px&quot;
        style=&quot;width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;&quot;
        loading=&quot;lazy&quot;
        decoding=&quot;async&quot;
      /&gt;
  &lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;What can be seen, can be automated&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Our platform had support for manually configurable subtitles already. Plone is based on hierarchical object database, not unlike filesystem with folders and files. Therefore, our platform was built to represent its content with folder-like “Media page” containers, which could contain any amount of related attachment items, like slides, lecture notes, and… subtitles!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
      class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-wrapper&quot;
      style=&quot;position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; &quot;
    &gt;
      &lt;a
    class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-link&quot;
    href=&quot;/static/a96a27c792c17b16ed8f81623f7d8128/5b587/moniviestin-example.png&quot;
    style=&quot;display: block&quot;
    target=&quot;_blank&quot;
    rel=&quot;noopener&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;span
    class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-background-image&quot;
    style=&quot;padding-bottom: 72.97297297297297%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/png;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;&quot;
  &gt;&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;img
        class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-image&quot;
        alt=&quot;moniviestin example&quot;
        title=&quot;moniviestin example&quot;
        src=&quot;/static/a96a27c792c17b16ed8f81623f7d8128/fcda8/moniviestin-example.png&quot;
        srcset=&quot;/static/a96a27c792c17b16ed8f81623f7d8128/12f09/moniviestin-example.png 148w,
/static/a96a27c792c17b16ed8f81623f7d8128/e4a3f/moniviestin-example.png 295w,
/static/a96a27c792c17b16ed8f81623f7d8128/fcda8/moniviestin-example.png 590w,
/static/a96a27c792c17b16ed8f81623f7d8128/efc66/moniviestin-example.png 885w,
/static/a96a27c792c17b16ed8f81623f7d8128/5b587/moniviestin-example.png 1010w&quot;
        sizes=&quot;(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px&quot;
        style=&quot;width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;&quot;
        loading=&quot;lazy&quot;
        decoding=&quot;async&quot;
      /&gt;
  &lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So, “Subtitles” was already a feature on our CMS based platform, and configurable within “Media page” manually through the user interface. But not only was “Subtitles” available to the end-users, it was also available through &lt;a href=&quot;https://plonerestapi.readthedocs.io/en/latest/&quot;&gt;Plone REST API&lt;/a&gt;. And Plone REST API provided out-of-the-box most of the necessary actions to fetch “Media pages” waiting for subtitles, post new subtitles, update existing subtitles, and confirm the updates according to the workflow.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Having workflow changes, addable “Subtitles”-content and scriptable REST API in place, one more Plone automation feature still needs to be mentioned: configurable event based actions, also known as “content rules”:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
      class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-wrapper&quot;
      style=&quot;position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; &quot;
    &gt;
      &lt;a
    class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-link&quot;
    href=&quot;/static/d3d0244cfdbc78451acef782ec4e38f8/42de8/moniviestin-content-rule.png&quot;
    style=&quot;display: block&quot;
    target=&quot;_blank&quot;
    rel=&quot;noopener&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;span
    class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-background-image&quot;
    style=&quot;padding-bottom: 106.75675675675676%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/png;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;&quot;
  &gt;&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;img
        class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-image&quot;
        alt=&quot;moniviestin content rule&quot;
        title=&quot;moniviestin content rule&quot;
        src=&quot;/static/d3d0244cfdbc78451acef782ec4e38f8/fcda8/moniviestin-content-rule.png&quot;
        srcset=&quot;/static/d3d0244cfdbc78451acef782ec4e38f8/12f09/moniviestin-content-rule.png 148w,
/static/d3d0244cfdbc78451acef782ec4e38f8/e4a3f/moniviestin-content-rule.png 295w,
/static/d3d0244cfdbc78451acef782ec4e38f8/fcda8/moniviestin-content-rule.png 590w,
/static/d3d0244cfdbc78451acef782ec4e38f8/efc66/moniviestin-content-rule.png 885w,
/static/d3d0244cfdbc78451acef782ec4e38f8/42de8/moniviestin-content-rule.png 1033w&quot;
        sizes=&quot;(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px&quot;
        style=&quot;width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;&quot;
        loading=&quot;lazy&quot;
        decoding=&quot;async&quot;
      /&gt;
  &lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For automated subtitles, Plone content rules made it simple to trigger automation service when “Publish with subtitles” was selected. Similarly it made simple to configure email notifications when automated subtitles were received.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Finally, let robots do the hard work&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;RPA, or Robotic Process Automation, is usually associated with expensive automation platforms with visual programming features. Yet, deep inside, this fancy term could simply mean any kind of script automation, being triggered by external events or timer, to perform some business value providing action. Actually, a very useful approach for casual automation…&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For automated subtitles, our team did not need to build tight integration between our video publishing platform and the selected ASR service. Neither did the team need to build any new continuosly running services to handle the integration. Our team simply needed to ensure that both ends had consumable HTTP APIs, and then write required scripts (“robots”) to handle the required communication between services.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The most obvious place for the required integration scripts was our existing Jenkins based RPA platform: &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.jenkins.io/&quot;&gt;Jenkins&lt;/a&gt; provides us job configuration, secrets management, webhooks endpoints, scheduled executions and archival of execution logs. Simply everything our team needed to manage the execution of these subtitle automation tasks.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
      class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-wrapper&quot;
      style=&quot;position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; &quot;
    &gt;
      &lt;a
    class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-link&quot;
    href=&quot;/static/d0b51abb980c4ddc10b9859eec82e905/37048/moniviestin-rpa-poll.png&quot;
    style=&quot;display: block&quot;
    target=&quot;_blank&quot;
    rel=&quot;noopener&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;span
    class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-background-image&quot;
    style=&quot;padding-bottom: 45.27027027027027%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/png;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;&quot;
  &gt;&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;img
        class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-image&quot;
        alt=&quot;moniviestin rpa poll&quot;
        title=&quot;moniviestin rpa poll&quot;
        src=&quot;/static/d0b51abb980c4ddc10b9859eec82e905/fcda8/moniviestin-rpa-poll.png&quot;
        srcset=&quot;/static/d0b51abb980c4ddc10b9859eec82e905/12f09/moniviestin-rpa-poll.png 148w,
/static/d0b51abb980c4ddc10b9859eec82e905/e4a3f/moniviestin-rpa-poll.png 295w,
/static/d0b51abb980c4ddc10b9859eec82e905/fcda8/moniviestin-rpa-poll.png 590w,
/static/d0b51abb980c4ddc10b9859eec82e905/efc66/moniviestin-rpa-poll.png 885w,
/static/d0b51abb980c4ddc10b9859eec82e905/c83ae/moniviestin-rpa-poll.png 1180w,
/static/d0b51abb980c4ddc10b9859eec82e905/37048/moniviestin-rpa-poll.png 1352w&quot;
        sizes=&quot;(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px&quot;
        style=&quot;width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;&quot;
        loading=&quot;lazy&quot;
        decoding=&quot;async&quot;
      /&gt;
  &lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In addition, our RPA Jenkins workers were already powered by &lt;a href=&quot;https://nixos.org/&quot;&gt;Nix package manager&lt;/a&gt; to provide all run-time dependencies for the automation scripts. I was told that just using Nix saved up to day in development time, because it provided complete and up-to-date ffmpeg installation for the integration scripts without any additional effort.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Let there be subtitles!&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Welcome our full subtitle automation story:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Video author selects “Publish with subtitles”.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Plone content rule calls Jenkins webhook to schedule a new robot.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Robot reads pending task from Plone, streams the video, extracts and converts the audio track, and submits the track to ASR service.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Jenkins schedules a new job to poll pending ASR jobs.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Robot reads completed task from ASR service, downloads the text, converts it into subtitles format and uploads the file to Plone.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Plone content rule notifies the video author with email that automatically generated subtitles are now available.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;???&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Profit.&lt;/p&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Static is fast, but CMS still required – a JAMstack story]]></title><description><![CDATA[An another iteration of our university’s new study guide web site has been completed. The project that started more than a year ago as a…]]></description><link>https://datakurre.pandala.org/2020/06/plone-volto-hasura-gatsby-mashup/</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://datakurre.pandala.org/2020/06/plone-volto-hasura-gatsby-mashup/</guid><pubDate>Fri, 12 Jun 2020 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><content:encoded>&lt;p&gt;An another iteration of &lt;a href=&quot;https://studyguide.jyu.fi/2020/&quot;&gt;our university’s new study guide web site&lt;/a&gt; has been completed. The project that started more than a year ago as a &lt;a href=&quot;https://jamstack.org/&quot;&gt;JAMstack&lt;/a&gt; experiment with &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.gatsbyjs.org/&quot;&gt;GatsbyJS&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;https://hasura.io/&quot;&gt;Hasura&lt;/a&gt;, has finally matured enough to get its long expected expansion: &lt;a href=&quot;http://voltocms.com/&quot;&gt;a content management system&lt;/a&gt;!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
      class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-wrapper&quot;
      style=&quot;position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; &quot;
    &gt;
      &lt;a
    class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-link&quot;
    href=&quot;/static/5f464ea574bdf596789162c011381ae8/4352a/study-guide-tabs.png&quot;
    style=&quot;display: block&quot;
    target=&quot;_blank&quot;
    rel=&quot;noopener&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;span
    class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-background-image&quot;
    style=&quot;padding-bottom: 50.67567567567568%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/png;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;&quot;
  &gt;&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;img
        class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-image&quot;
        alt=&quot;study guide tabs&quot;
        title=&quot;study guide tabs&quot;
        src=&quot;/static/5f464ea574bdf596789162c011381ae8/fcda8/study-guide-tabs.png&quot;
        srcset=&quot;/static/5f464ea574bdf596789162c011381ae8/12f09/study-guide-tabs.png 148w,
/static/5f464ea574bdf596789162c011381ae8/e4a3f/study-guide-tabs.png 295w,
/static/5f464ea574bdf596789162c011381ae8/fcda8/study-guide-tabs.png 590w,
/static/5f464ea574bdf596789162c011381ae8/efc66/study-guide-tabs.png 885w,
/static/5f464ea574bdf596789162c011381ae8/c83ae/study-guide-tabs.png 1180w,
/static/5f464ea574bdf596789162c011381ae8/4352a/study-guide-tabs.png 1364w&quot;
        sizes=&quot;(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px&quot;
        style=&quot;width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;&quot;
        loading=&quot;lazy&quot;
        decoding=&quot;async&quot;
      /&gt;
  &lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In the beginning there was data. A lot of it. A great amount of granular JSON chunks, to be turned into fast and well connected study guide web site. Regularly updated, of course. For years we had solved similar use cases by building and synchronizing CMS content out of more or less structured data. This time we had not enough resources for a such “sophisticated” CMS integration, but we had to look for more agile alternatives – think out of the box. We chose to go JAMstack, with GatsbyJS.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Hasura – the magical GraphQL gateway&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;At first, of course, we had to make sense of our data. GatsbyJS requires to use &lt;a href=&quot;https://graphql.org/&quot;&gt;GraphQL&lt;/a&gt; queries to select the published content. By chance, we found &lt;a href=&quot;https://hasura.io/&quot;&gt;Hasura&lt;/a&gt;, which is designed to turn any &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.postgresql.org/&quot;&gt;PostgreSQL&lt;/a&gt; database into well-connected GraphQL API. So, we built a pipeline to dump our JSON data into JSONB columns within simple PostgreSQL tables. Once the data was in the database, and we learned which parts we really needed, we could build dynamic database views to expose the data exactly as we wanted.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
      class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-wrapper&quot;
      style=&quot;position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; &quot;
    &gt;
      &lt;a
    class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-link&quot;
    href=&quot;/static/04310f78ea07819edaca486b69c973d6/4352a/hasura-view.png&quot;
    style=&quot;display: block&quot;
    target=&quot;_blank&quot;
    rel=&quot;noopener&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;span
    class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-background-image&quot;
    style=&quot;padding-bottom: 50.67567567567568%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/png;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;&quot;
  &gt;&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;img
        class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-image&quot;
        alt=&quot;hasura view&quot;
        title=&quot;hasura view&quot;
        src=&quot;/static/04310f78ea07819edaca486b69c973d6/fcda8/hasura-view.png&quot;
        srcset=&quot;/static/04310f78ea07819edaca486b69c973d6/12f09/hasura-view.png 148w,
/static/04310f78ea07819edaca486b69c973d6/e4a3f/hasura-view.png 295w,
/static/04310f78ea07819edaca486b69c973d6/fcda8/hasura-view.png 590w,
/static/04310f78ea07819edaca486b69c973d6/efc66/hasura-view.png 885w,
/static/04310f78ea07819edaca486b69c973d6/c83ae/hasura-view.png 1180w,
/static/04310f78ea07819edaca486b69c973d6/4352a/hasura-view.png 1364w&quot;
        sizes=&quot;(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px&quot;
        style=&quot;width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;&quot;
        loading=&quot;lazy&quot;
        decoding=&quot;async&quot;
      /&gt;
  &lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As designed, Hasura was able to publish those views as GraphQL types and connect them with the relations we needed. Suddenly we had complete GraphQL API for our data. Almost, but not quite entirely unlike, magic. Awesome. Really.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
      class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-wrapper&quot;
      style=&quot;position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; &quot;
    &gt;
      &lt;a
    class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-link&quot;
    href=&quot;/static/187314df6781ba7b99a6f17aa346d605/4352a/hasura-relationships.png&quot;
    style=&quot;display: block&quot;
    target=&quot;_blank&quot;
    rel=&quot;noopener&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;span
    class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-background-image&quot;
    style=&quot;padding-bottom: 50.67567567567568%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/png;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;&quot;
  &gt;&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;img
        class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-image&quot;
        alt=&quot;hasura relationships&quot;
        title=&quot;hasura relationships&quot;
        src=&quot;/static/187314df6781ba7b99a6f17aa346d605/fcda8/hasura-relationships.png&quot;
        srcset=&quot;/static/187314df6781ba7b99a6f17aa346d605/12f09/hasura-relationships.png 148w,
/static/187314df6781ba7b99a6f17aa346d605/e4a3f/hasura-relationships.png 295w,
/static/187314df6781ba7b99a6f17aa346d605/fcda8/hasura-relationships.png 590w,
/static/187314df6781ba7b99a6f17aa346d605/efc66/hasura-relationships.png 885w,
/static/187314df6781ba7b99a6f17aa346d605/c83ae/hasura-relationships.png 1180w,
/static/187314df6781ba7b99a6f17aa346d605/4352a/hasura-relationships.png 1364w&quot;
        sizes=&quot;(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px&quot;
        style=&quot;width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;&quot;
        loading=&quot;lazy&quot;
        decoding=&quot;async&quot;
      /&gt;
  &lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But publishing all that structured data with fast and accessible user experience was not enough. More information was required to be included on the site. This time with images, video embeds and attachments. And the master system was not designed to handle that.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;After all, a real CMS was required.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Volto – a breeze of fresh air&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Lucky us, we had just right CMS product and experience available. &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.plone.com/&quot;&gt;Plone CMS&lt;/a&gt; with its latest user interface, &lt;a href=&quot;https://volto.kitconcept.com/&quot;&gt;Volto&lt;/a&gt;, provided us both hierarchical object database and modern user interface required for managing the additional content. Plone shines in managing content in folder tree like hierarchies, and sharing access rights for them accordingly. Volto, on the other hand, makes Plone snappier and easier to use than ever.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
      class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-wrapper&quot;
      style=&quot;position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; &quot;
    &gt;
      &lt;a
    class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-link&quot;
    href=&quot;/static/c0446761d591f0bcedfc6e70c169d0a3/4352a/volto-contents.png&quot;
    style=&quot;display: block&quot;
    target=&quot;_blank&quot;
    rel=&quot;noopener&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;span
    class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-background-image&quot;
    style=&quot;padding-bottom: 50.67567567567568%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/png;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;&quot;
  &gt;&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;img
        class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-image&quot;
        alt=&quot;volto contents&quot;
        title=&quot;volto contents&quot;
        src=&quot;/static/c0446761d591f0bcedfc6e70c169d0a3/fcda8/volto-contents.png&quot;
        srcset=&quot;/static/c0446761d591f0bcedfc6e70c169d0a3/12f09/volto-contents.png 148w,
/static/c0446761d591f0bcedfc6e70c169d0a3/e4a3f/volto-contents.png 295w,
/static/c0446761d591f0bcedfc6e70c169d0a3/fcda8/volto-contents.png 590w,
/static/c0446761d591f0bcedfc6e70c169d0a3/efc66/volto-contents.png 885w,
/static/c0446761d591f0bcedfc6e70c169d0a3/c83ae/volto-contents.png 1180w,
/static/c0446761d591f0bcedfc6e70c169d0a3/4352a/volto-contents.png 1364w&quot;
        sizes=&quot;(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px&quot;
        style=&quot;width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;&quot;
        loading=&quot;lazy&quot;
        decoding=&quot;async&quot;
      /&gt;
  &lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And when it comes to &lt;a href=&quot;https://collective.github.io/gatsby-source-plone/&quot;&gt;Plone as a data source for GatsbyJS&lt;/a&gt;: I personally mentored Google Summer of Code students both in &lt;a href=&quot;https://summerofcode.withgoogle.com/archive/2018/projects/5034509258981376/&quot;&gt;2018&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;https://summerofcode.withgoogle.com/archive/2019/projects/5770661249679360/&quot;&gt;2019&lt;/a&gt;, and then continued the work, to make sure that Plone integrates perfectly with any GatsbyJS project.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The last piece in our puzzle was to connect Volto authored Plone CMS content with our structured data from the Hasura powered GraphQL API. The flexibility of Plone CMS, with fresh customization possibilities provided by Volto, enabled our solution:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Plone ships with out-of-the-box customizable structured content types. Without any custom code, we were able to enhance our Volto-editable pages with metadata fields to store the connecting information. This also made the data available in Plone REST API for GatsbyJS data source integration.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
      class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-wrapper&quot;
      style=&quot;position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; &quot;
    &gt;
      &lt;a
    class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-link&quot;
    href=&quot;/static/f064a992740a38bcb5cc52b88dab8caa/4352a/plone-dexterity-editor.png&quot;
    style=&quot;display: block&quot;
    target=&quot;_blank&quot;
    rel=&quot;noopener&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;span
